A CV-screening system used for recruitment, selection, or filtering of job applicants is classified as **high-risk** under the EU AI Act (Annex III, point 4(a): AI systems intended to be used for recruitment or selection of natural persons, in particular to filter job applications and evaluate candidates).

The key verifiable property to enforce is **non-discrimination / demographic fairness**: the system's selection or scoring outcomes must not produce disparate impact across protected attributes (gender, age, ethnicity, disability, etc.). This is typically operationalized as a statistical parity constraint, e.g. demographic parity difference or disparate impact ratio (the "four-fifths rule": selection rate of any protected group ≥ 0.8 × rate of the most-favored group), measured on a held-out audit dataset and continuously monitored in production. Article 10 (data governance, bias examination) and Article 15 (accuracy, robustness) provide the legal basis, and the property is verifiable by computing group-conditional selection rates and asserting the ratio stays within the defined threshold.
